  "doc_id": "9647",
  "text": "As the most essential tasks in large-scale environments, distributed operations such as joins and aggregations can incur significant time costs on network communications and hence improving their execution efficiency would have a significant impact on the overall performance of current big data analytics. In fact, these operations have been extensively studied in the field of data management, and large number of methods have been proposed to improve their performance. For example, for distributed join executions, current research focuses on the challenge on how to efficiently move data, either in the presence of different join workloads (e.g., skew) or different computing platforms (e.g., clusters and Cloud) or both [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] , [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] , [CITATION_5] , [CITATION_6] . Their main target is either to reduce network traffic or to improve load-balancing or both, so as to balance computations and improve network communication time.",
